            <div>
                <head>Comments</head>
                <p xml:id="KR6v0299-start">
                    <seg corresp="#KR6v0299_CBETA_000-0005a0401.s3" xml:lang="en" resp="#schwermann" modified="2023-06-14T16:38:39.074+09:00">As for the first and fourth ships, the ambassadors boarded the ships? Or: The ambassadors on board of the first and fourth ships boarded?</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6v0299_CBETA_000-0005a0401.s6" xml:lang="en" resp="#schwermann" modified="2023-06-14T16:46:27.721+09:00">temporal reference (三箇日) postverbal</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6v0299_CBETA_000-0005a0510.s5" xml:lang="en" resp="#schwermann" modified="2023-06-14T16:45:52.102+09:00">temporal reference (五箇日) preverbal</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6v0299_CBETA_000-0005a1719.s7" xml:lang="en" resp="#schwermann" modified="2023-06-14T16:50:38.316+09:00">Above: 人咸謂</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6v0299_CBETA_000-0005a0920.s18" xml:lang="en" resp="#schwermann" modified="2023-06-14T16:51:56.53+09:00">Below: 人眾咸云</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6v0299_CBETA_000-0005a1719.s9" xml:lang="en" resp="#schwermann" modified="2023-06-14T17:10:38.093+09:00">What is the object governed by 見? Is it the "whitish water" (白水) referred to above? Or is the sentence ungrammatical as it stands? If yes, would 見 have to be substituted by wàng 望, "look/gaze into the distance"? For 申云, see below.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR6v0299_CBETA_000-0005a1719.s16" xml:lang="en" resp="#schwermann" modified="2023-06-14T17:09:50.501+09:00">According to CBETA, the collocation 申云 is rarely found in other texts but quite frequent in Ennin's diary.</seg>
                </p>
            </div>
